+- id: SCL-009
+  group: SCL
+  priority: P1
+  status: IMPLEMENTED
+  section: 19. Autonomous runtime and capability requirements
+  requirement: '`clone_baseline()` MUST NOT redundantly re-clone the same repository over the network multiple times within
+    a single `supervise_repo()` run, MUST still observe genuinely current upstream state on every call regardless of caller
+    or process lifetime, and a clone failure MUST degrade to an observable `BLOCKED` outcome (with evidence) rather than an
+    uncaught process abort. **Found live, 2026-07-22**, triaging a real timeout on the newly-published `aspose-words-foss/Aspose.Words-FOSS-for-.NET`
+    (15,522 files, ~40x the enabled Java pilot''s file count): tracing one `supervise` run''s clone call sites found `clone_baseline()`
+    is called independently by ~7-9 stateless capabilities with no shared per-run repo view (decision #26(b)) — the SAME repository
+    was being cloned over the network roughly 9-17 times per run, each an independent roll against `SCL-004`''s own already-measured
+    158s-1004s clone-time variance for the identical repo. This is a structural cause of cross-rerun inconsistency (more redundant
+    clones = more chances to draw the long tail and time out), and a latent correctness gap (different capabilities could
+    observe different upstream revisions if a push landed mid-run, since nothing guaranteed all ~9 clones saw the same commit)
+    -- not merely a "timeout too short" symptom. **Design corrected during this same pass, not just built once**: a first
+    version memoized per-process and had `supervise_repo()` call an `invalidate_baseline_clone()` before its own top-level
+    clone, reasoning "a run is one `supervise_repo()` call." A full-suite run the same session found that reasoning incomplete:
+    two pre-existing `tests/unit/test_specialists.py` tests (`test_upstream_edit_between_runs_is_upstream_changed`, `test_a_success_after_failures_resets_the_counter`)
+    call a specialist''s own `run()` directly, twice, in one process -- a different top-level entry point the invalidate-in-`supervise_repo()`-only
+    design never covered, and there is no bounded, exhaustively-enumerable list of such entry points to patch one at a time.
+    **Final, built and live-proven mechanism**: `clone_baseline()` validates its own memo against a cheap `remote_head_sha()`
+    probe (a `git ls-remote`, ~1-15s -- reusing this project''s own decision #40/ORC-006 freshness-probe pattern) instead
+    of trusting process lifetime; this makes every caller correct automatically with zero invalidation bookkeeping anywhere,
+    and `invalidate_baseline_clone()` was removed as unneeded. Also built: `env.py::git_clone_timeout_seconds()` (`GIT_CLONE_TIMEOUT_SECONDS`,
+    default raised 300s→600s, evidence-informed headroom over `SCL-004`''s measured band, not a guarantee of covering its
+    1004s outlier); a bounded, transient-failure-only retry (2 attempts, 5s/15s backoff, returncode 124 or known-transient
+    git stderr text only -- a real error like "not found" fails fast); `supervise_repo()` catches `GitSafetyError` from its
+    own clone call and returns `SuperviseResult(status="BLOCKED", blocked_reason="baseline_clone_failed:...")` with a written
+    evidence bundle, instead of the previous uncaught propagation to the CLI''s bare `error: ...` print and exit 3. **Named
+    cost, not hidden**: reuse now costs one network probe (~1-15s) rather than being free, in exchange for correctness that
+    doesn''t depend on any caller remembering to invalidate. A concurrent session, working from the intermediate (invalidate-based)
+    design, independently patched the same two `test_specialists.py` tests at the test layer (an autouse `_clean_clone_memo`
+    fixture + explicit `reset_clone_memo()` calls) -- harmless, left in place as extra defense-in-depth, but superseded as
+    the actual mechanism of correctness by the SHA-probe design, which makes both tests pass without needing their own patch
+    to do so. **Deliberately not done this pass** (named, not silently deferred): generalizing the git-tree-API no-clone path
+    (`SCL-004`) beyond profiling to the other ~7 cloning capabilities -- a larger, riskier lift, unproven for non-manifest
+    file reads (README/community-file content); revisit if portfolio-scale wall-clock cost is still too high after this fix.'
+  acceptance_evidence: '`tests/unit/test_gitsafety.py::TestCloneBaselineAndWork`/`TestCloneBaselineRetryAndTimeout` (memoization
+    reuse, a real upstream commit invalidates the memo via the SHA probe with no explicit reset, a failed probe falls back
+    to a real clone rather than a stale reuse, self-heals if the directory vanishes, retries a synthetic timeout then succeeds,
+    does not retry a real not-found error, gives up after max attempts, timeout reads the env var) + `tests/unit/test_supervisor_loop.py::TestBaselineCloneFailureDegradesGracefully`
+    (clone failure returns `BLOCKED` with evidence, not an uncaught exception; behaves identically with evidence disabled)
+    + the full unit suite, including `test_specialists.py`''s two previously-broken tests, passing clean.'
+  traceability_raw: 'SCL-004; decision #26(b); decision #49; found, redesigned, and fixed 2026-07-22 during the registry-readiness/clone-reliability
